  "doc_id": "22397",
  "text": "Our data suggest a scheme for how the pre-TCR may control wnt signaling. Nonphosphorylated, active ␤-catenin is present in RAG-1-deficient thymocytes prior to the induction of pre-TCR signaling. Thus ␤-catenin stabilization in thymocytes occurs independently of the pre-TCR, most likely via the wnt-dependent inhibition of the ␤-catenin phosphorylation complex. There is indeed evidence that components of the wnt signaling cascade, which are upstream of ␤-catenin are involved in thymocyte development. Overexpression of antagonists of the wnt receptor Fz/LRP in thymic organ cultures impairs thymocyte expansion. [CITATION_1] Moreover, transgenic overexpression of axin, a negative regulator of wnt signaling, which promotes ␤-catenin degradation, resulted in widespread thymocyte apoptosis. [CITATION_2] Thus, the available evidence suggests that active, signaling-competent ␤-catenin is dependent on wnt signals and independent of the pre-TCR.",
